[
    {
        "content": "<p>We have a bunch of versions of the first isomorphism theorem, but is there one for <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=MonoidHom.ker#doc\">docs#MonoidHom.ker</a> ?</p>",
        "id": 469024802,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1725956364
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Probably not because this is more subtle: the quotient has to be taken by the equivalence relation which is generated by <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>f</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>y</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> f(x)=f(y) </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 469049641,
        "sender_full_name": "Antoine Chambert-Loir",
        "timestamp": 1725962671
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, the kernel isn't enough information to determine the image for monoids (for example if you give Fin n the monoid structure it should have, which is x+y=n-1 if in reality it's &gt;= n-1) then the obvious map from Nat is surjective with trivial kernel.</p>",
        "id": 469082750,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1725972920
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>We do have <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Con#doc\">docs#Con</a></p>",
        "id": 469083248,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1725973039
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>These are setoids which are \"compatible with multiplication\".</p>",
        "id": 469083360,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1725973064
    },
    {
        "content": "<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Mathlib</span>\n\n<span class=\"kd\">example</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">α</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"bp\">*</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">Monoid</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">α</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">S</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Con</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">α</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Monoid</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">S.Quotient</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">inferInstance</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 469084010,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1725973181
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That's essentially the only way to talk about quotients of monoids. You can take whatever relation you like and look at the congruence relation generated by it with <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=conGen#doc\">docs#conGen</a> and only then take the quotient.</p>",
        "id": 469084375,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1725973261
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>My earlier claim is that for good structures which have subtraction, the compatible equivalence relation generated by <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>f</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>y</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f(x)=f(y)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> is determined by the class of the adequate zero/one element. But <code>quotient_rel_equiv_range</code> would work as well. <br>\nThe analogue for semirings is missing too.</p>",
        "id": 469107256,
        "sender_full_name": "Antoine Chambert-Loir",
        "timestamp": 1725978080
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I should specify that I am in fact working with groups</p>",
        "id": 469153821,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1725987141
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But to my understanding <code>MonoidHom</code> is still the structure to be used</p>",
        "id": 469153924,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1725987168
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Is there some theorem like <code>Con.ker = MomoidHom.ker</code>?</p>",
        "id": 469154039,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1725987196
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh, for groups everything works as you expect. You probably want to take a look around <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/GroupTheory/QuotientGroup/Basic.html#QuotientAddGroup.quotientKerEquivOfRightInverse\">QuotientAddGroup.quotientKerEquivOfRightInverse</a></p>",
        "id": 469155420,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1725987525
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"459227\">Violeta Hernández</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/217875-Is-there-code-for-X.3F/topic/MonoidHom.2Equotient_ker_equiv_range/near/469024802\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>We have a bunch of versions of the first isomorphism theorem, but is there one for <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=MonoidHom.ker#doc\">docs#MonoidHom.ker</a> ?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I'm confused, isn't <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=QuotientGroup.quotientKerEquivRange#doc\">docs#QuotientGroup.quotientKerEquivRange</a> precisely what you're asking for?</p>",
        "id": 469161307,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1725988982
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Or did you mean to ask about <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=MonoidHom.mker#doc\">docs#MonoidHom.mker</a>, which seems to be what everyone is assuming you meant?</p>",
        "id": 469161447,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1725989015
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"310045\">Eric Wieser</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/217875-Is-there-code-for-X.3F/topic/MonoidHom.2Equotient_ker_equiv_range/near/469161307\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"459227\">Violeta Hernández</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/217875-Is-there-code-for-X.3F/topic/MonoidHom.2Equotient_ker_equiv_range/near/469024802\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>We have a bunch of versions of the first isomorphism theorem, but is there one for <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=MonoidHom.ker#doc\">docs#MonoidHom.ker</a> ?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I'm confused, isn't <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=QuotientGroup.quotientKerEquivRange#doc\">docs#QuotientGroup.quotientKerEquivRange</a> precisely what you're asking for?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Ah, I think that's it</p>",
        "id": 469205038,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1725999993
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That's quite an annoying naming discrepancy, I was finding all the versions of this theorem except for this one</p>",
        "id": 469205150,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1726000049
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think that's because the isomorphism theorems for groups were the first ones written, back when there were no naming convention for these things? I found it annoying too, and it would be great if someone makes them consistent.</p>",
        "id": 469223979,
        "sender_full_name": "David Ang",
        "timestamp": 1726006524
    }
]